Definition 1.2.9. Let $n$ be a nonnegative integer. We define the notion of a strict $n$-category by induction on $n$: $(a)$ If $n=0$, then a strict $n$-category is a set. $(b)$ If $n>0$, then a strict $n$-category is a category enriched over strict $(n-1)$-categories. In other words, a strict $n$-category $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ consists of the following data: $(i)$ A collection of objects $X,Y,Z,\ldots$ $(ii)$ For every pair of objects $X,Y\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, a strict $(n-1)$-category $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$. $(iii)$ Identity objects $\operatorname{id}_{X}\in\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}}(X,X)$ and composition maps $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)\times% \operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(Y,Z)% \rightarrow\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,% Z),$ satisfying the usual unit and associativity conditions.
Definition 2.2.10. We let $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ denote the $(\infty,n)$-category associated to the $n$-fold Segal space $\operatorname{{\bf PBord}}_{n}$ defined above. More precisely, we define $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ to be an $n$-fold complete Segal space which is obtained from $\operatorname{{\bf PBord}}_{n}$ by completion (see Remark 2.1.40).
Definition 4.1.1. Let ${\mathbf{S}}$ be a symmetric monoidal $(\infty,1)$-category. We will define a sequence of symmetric monoidal $(\infty,1)$-categories $\operatorname{Alg}^{(n)}({\mathbf{S}})$ using induction as follows: • If $n=1$, we let $\operatorname{Alg}^{(n)}({\mathbf{S}})=\operatorname{Alg}({\mathbf{S}})$ be the $(\infty,1)$-category of associative algebra objects of ${\mathbf{S}}$. • If $n>1$, we let $\operatorname{Alg}^{(n)}({\mathbf{S}})=\operatorname{Alg}(\operatorname{Alg}^{% (n-1)}({\mathbf{S}}))$ be the $(\infty,1)$-category of associative algebra objects in $\operatorname{Alg}^{(n-1)}({\mathbf{S}})$. We will refer to objects of $\operatorname{Alg}^{(n)}({\mathbf{S}})$ as $E_{n}$-algebras in ${\mathbf{S}}$.
Definition 2.1.3. The category $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}$ of combinatorial simplices is defined as follows: • The objects of $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}$ are the nonnegative integers. For each $n\geq 0$, we let $[n]$ denote the corresponding object of $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}$. • Given a pair of integers $m,n\geq 0$, we define $\operatorname{Hom}_{\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}}([m],[n])$ to be the set of nonstrictly increasing maps $f:\{0<1<\ldots<m\}\rightarrow\{0<1<\ldots<n\}$. Let ${\mathbf{A}}$ be an arbitrary category. A simplicial object of ${\mathbf{A}}$ is a functor from $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}^{op}$ into ${\mathbf{A}}$.
Definition 3.3.3. Let $\pi:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ be a functor between $(\infty,1)$-categories, and let $\overline{f}:C\rightarrow C^{\prime}$ be a morphism in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$. We will say that $\overline{f}$ is $\pi$-coCartesian if the following condition is satisfied: • For every object $C^{\prime\prime}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, the diagram of $\infty$-groupoids $\xymatrix{\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(C^{% \prime},C^{\prime\prime})\ar[r]\ar[d]&\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{% \operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(C,C^{\prime\prime})\ar[d]\\ \operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}}(\pi(C^{\prime% }),\pi(C^{\prime\prime}))\ar[r]&\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{% \operatorname{\mathcal{D}}}(\pi(C),\pi(C^{\prime\prime}))}$ is a homotopy pullback square. We say that the functor $\pi$ is a coCartesian fibration if the following condition is satisfied: for every object $C\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ and every morphism $f:\pi(C)\rightarrow D$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$, there exists a $\pi$-coCartesian morphism $\overline{f}:C\rightarrow\overline{D}$ lifting $f$.
Definition 2.1.23. An $(\infty,1)$-category is a complete Segal space.
Definition 3.4.4. Let $M$ be a closed $(n-2)$-manifold, and let $B$ be a morphism in $\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}(M)$. A framed function on $B$ consists of the following data: $(1)$ A function $f\in\operatorname{Fun}(B)$ which is a generalized Morse function. $(2)$ For every critical point $b$ of $f$ having index $m$, a collection of tangent vectors $v_{1},\ldots,v_{m}\in T_{B,b}$ satisfying $H(v_{i},v_{j})=\begin{cases}0&\text{if }i\neq j\\ -2&\text{if }i=j,\end{cases}$ where $H$ denotes the Hessian of $f$ at $b$.
Definition 2.3.21. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ be a monoidal $(\infty,n)$-category. We will say that an object $X\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ is fully dualizable if it belongs to the essential image of the functor $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}^{\operatorname{fd}}\rightarrow\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}$.
Definition 4.4.1. Let $0\leq k\leq n$ be integers, and let $M$ be an $m$-manifold equipped with an $n$-framing. A $k$-framed submanifold of $M$ consists of the following data: $(1)$ A submanifold $M_{0}\subseteq M$ of codimension $(n-k)$. Together with the $n$-framing of $M$, the normal bundle to $M_{0}$ in $M$ determines a “Gauss map” $g:M_{0}\rightarrow\operatorname{Gr}_{n-k,n}$, where $\operatorname{Gr}_{n-k,n}$ denote the real Grassmannian $\operatorname{O}(n)/(\operatorname{O}(k)\times\operatorname{O}(n-k))$. $(2)$ A nullhomotopy of the map $g$. If $M$ is equipped with boundary (or with corners), then we will assume that $M_{0}$ intersections the boundary $\operatorname{\partial}M$ (or the corners) transversely.
Definition 2.2.7. We let $\operatorname{{\bf Cob}_{t}^{un}}(n)$ denote the $(\infty,1)$-category associated to the Segal space $\operatorname{{\bf PreCob}}(n)_{\bullet}$ by Construction 2.1.17. If we adopt Definition 2.1.23, we can be more precise: we let $\operatorname{{\bf Cob}_{t}^{un}}(n)$ denote the complete Segal space obtained by completing $\operatorname{{\bf PreCob}}(n)_{\bullet}$ (see Remark 2.1.24).
Definition 3.5.10. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ be an $(\infty,n)$-category. If $n=0$, then a local system of abelian groups on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ is a functor from $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ to the $($ordinary$)$ category of abelian groups. If $n>0$, then a local system of abelian groups on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ consists of the following data: $(i)$ For every pair of objects $x,y\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, a local system $\operatorname{\mathcal{A}}_{x,y}$ of abelian groups on the $(\infty,n-1)$-category $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(x,y)$. $(ii)$ For every triple of objects $x,y,z\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, a map of local systems $m_{x,y,z}:p_{0}^{\ast}\operatorname{\mathcal{A}}_{x,y}\times p_{1}^{\ast}% \operatorname{\mathcal{A}}_{y,z}\rightarrow c^{\ast}\operatorname{\mathcal{A}}% _{x,z}.$ Here $p_{0}$ and $p_{1}$ denote the projection maps of $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(x,y)\times% \operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(y,z)$ onto $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(x,y)$ and $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(y,z)$, respectively, and $c$ the composition map $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(x,y)\times% \operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(y,z)% \rightarrow\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(x,z)$. The collection of maps $\{m_{x,y,z}\}_{x,y,z\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}$ is required to satisfy some natural associativity conditions which we will not make explicit.
Definition 2.1.37. Let $n>0$, and let $X$ be an $n$-fold simplicial space. We will regard $X$ as a simplicial object $X_{\bullet}$ in the category of $(n-1)$-fold simplicial spaces. We will say that $X$ is an $n$-fold Segal space if the following conditions are satisfied: $(A1)$ For every $0\leq k\leq m$, the diagram $\xymatrix{X_{m}\ar[r]\ar[d]&X_{k}\ar[d]\\ X_{m-k}\ar[r]&X_{0}}$ of Definition 2.1.15 is a homotopy pullback square (of $(n-1)$-fold simplicial spaces). $(A2)$ The $(n-1)$-fold simplicial space $X_{0}$ is essentially constant. $(A3)$ Each of the $(n-1)$-uple simplicial spaces $X_{k}$ is an $(n-1)$-dimensional Segal space. We will say that an $n$-fold Segal space $X_{\bullet}$ is complete if it satisfies the following additional conditions: $(A4)$ Each of the $(n-1)$-dimensional Segal spaces $X_{n}$ is complete (we regard this condition as vacuous when $n=1$). $(A5)$ Let $Y_{\bullet}$ be the simplicial space described by the formula $Y_{k}=X_{k,0,\ldots,0}$; note that condition $(A1)$ guarantees that $Y_{\bullet}$ is a Segal space. Then $Y_{\bullet}$ is complete.
Definition 1.2.6. Let $k$ be a field. An $2$-extended topological field theory of dimension $n$ is a symmetric monoidal functor $Z:{\text{\bf Cob}}_{2}(n)\rightarrow\operatorname{{\bf Vect}}_{2}(k)$ between $2$-categories.
Incorrect Definition 1.4.2. Let $k$ be a field. A chain-complex valued topological field theory of dimension $n$ is a symmetric monoidal functor $\overline{Z}:{\text{\bf Cob}}(n)\rightarrow\operatorname{{\bf Chain}}(k)$, where $\operatorname{{\bf Chain}}(k)$ denotes the category of chain complexes of $k$-vector spaces $\ldots V_{2}\rightarrow V_{1}\rightarrow V_{0}\rightarrow V_{-1}\rightarrow V_% {-2}\rightarrow\ldots$
Definition 2.3.11. We will say that a $2$-category $\operatorname{\mathcal{E}}$ has adjoints for $1$-morphisms if the following conditions are satisfied: $(1)$ For every $1$-morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{E}}$, there exists another $1$-morphism $g:Y\rightarrow X$ and a $2$-morphism $u:\operatorname{id}_{X}\rightarrow g\circ f$ which is the unit of an adjunction. $(2)$ For every $1$-morphism $g:Y\rightarrow X$ in $\operatorname{\mathcal{E}}$, there exists another $1$-morphism $f:X\rightarrow Y$ and a $2$-morphism $u:\operatorname{id}_{X}\rightarrow g\circ f$ which is the unit of an adjunction.
Definition Sketch 4.2.10. We define a symmetric monoidal $(\infty,2)$-category $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$ informally as follows: • The objects of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$ are oriented $0$-manifolds. • Given a pair of objects $X,Y\in\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$, a $1$-morphism from $X$ to $Y$ is an oriented bordism $B:X\rightarrow Y$. • Given a pair of $1$-morphsims $B,B^{\prime}:X\rightarrow Y$ in $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{or},\operatorname{nc}}$, a $2$-morphism from $B$ to $B^{\prime}$ in $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$ is an oriented bordism $\Sigma:B\rightarrow B^{\prime}$ (which is trivial along $X$ and $Y$) with the following property: every connected component of $\Sigma$ has nonempty intersection with $B$. • Higher morphisms in $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$ are given by (orientation preserving) diffeomorphisms, isotopies between diffeomorphisms, and so forth. • The symmetric monoidal structure on $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{2}^{\operatorname{nc}}$ is given by the formation of disjoint unions.
Definition 2.1.15. Let $X_{\bullet}$ be a simplicial space. We say that $X_{\bullet}$ is a Segal space if the following condition is satisfied: $(\ast)$ For every pair of integers $m,n\geq 0$, the diagram $\xymatrix{X_{m+n}\ar[r]\ar[d]&X_{m}\ar[d]\\ X_{n}\ar[r]&X_{0}}$ is a homotopy pullback square.
Definition 3.3.11. A skeletal sequence $($of length $n$$)$ is a diagram $\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}_{1}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{1}}}{{\rightarrow}}% \operatorname{\mathcal{B}}_{2}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{2}}}{{\rightarrow}}% \ldots\stackrel{{\scriptstyle f_{n-1}}}{{\rightarrow}}\operatorname{\mathcal{B% }}_{n}$ with the following properies: $(1)$ Each $\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}_{k}$ is a symmetric monoidal $(\infty,k)$-category. $(2)$ Each $f_{k}$ is a $(k-1)$-connective symmetric monoidal functor. $(3)$ Every object of $\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}_{1}$ is dualizable. $(4)$ For $2\leq k\leq n$, every morphism $\alpha:{\bf 1}\rightarrow X$ in $\Omega^{k-2}\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}_{k}$ admits a left adjoint.
Definition 2.3.1. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ be a monoidal category: that is, a category equipped with a tensor product operation $\otimes:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\times\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow% \operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ which is unital and associative (but not necessarily commutative) up to coherent isomorphism. Let $V$ be an object of $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$. We will say that an object $V^{\vee}$ is a right dual of $V$ if there exist maps $\operatorname{ev}_{V}:V\otimes V^{\vee}\rightarrow{\bf 1}\quad\quad% \operatorname{coev}_{V}:{\bf 1}\rightarrow V^{\vee}\otimes V$ such that the compositions $V\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\operatorname{id}_{V}\otimes\operatorname{coev}_{V}}}{% {\longrightarrow}}V\otimes V^{\vee}\otimes V\stackrel{{\scriptstyle% \operatorname{ev}_{V}\otimes\operatorname{id}_{V}}}{{\longrightarrow}}V$ $V^{\vee}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\operatorname{coev}_{V}\otimes\operatorname{id}% _{V^{\vee}}}}{{\longrightarrow}}V^{\vee}\otimes V\otimes V^{\vee}\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle\operatorname{id}_{V^{\vee}}\otimes\operatorname{ev}_{V}}}{{% \rightarrow}}V^{\vee}$ coincide with $\operatorname{id}_{V}$ and $\operatorname{id}_{V^{\vee}}$, respectively. In this case, we will also say that $V$ is a left dual of $V^{\vee}$.
Definition 4.1.7. We will say that a monoidal $(\infty,1)$-category ${\mathbf{S}}$ is good if ${\mathbf{S}}$ admits small sifted colimits, and the tensor product functor $\otimes:{\mathbf{S}}\times{\mathbf{S}}\rightarrow{\mathbf{S}}$ preserves small sifted colimits (see [17] for an explanation of this terminology).
Definition 2.1.5. A simplicial set is a simplicial object in the category of sets.
Definition 3.3.4. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ and $\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ be symmetric monoidal $(\infty,1)$-categories. A symmetric monoidal coCartesian fibration from $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ to $\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ is a symmetric monoidal functor $\pi:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ which is a coCartesian fibration and such that the collection of $\pi$-coCartesian morphisms in $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ is stable under tensor products.
Definition 2.1.27. Let $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}_{0}$ denote the subcategory of $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}$ with the same objects, where the morphisms from $[m]$ to $[n]$ are given by strictly increasing maps of linearly ordered sets $\{0<1<\ldots<m\}\rightarrow\{0<1<\ldots<n\}$. A semisimplicial object of a category ${\mathbf{A}}$ is a functor from $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}_{0}^{op}$ into ${\mathbf{A}}$.
Definition 3.4.9. Let $M$ be a closed $(n-2)$-manifold, let $B$ be a $1$-morphism in $\operatorname{\mathcal{B}}(M)$, and let $k$ be an integer. We will say that a framed function $f$ on $B$ is $k$-typical if, for every critical point $b$ of $f$, one of the following conditions holds: $(1)$ The function $f$ has a nondegenerate critical point at $b$ of index $\leq k$. $(2)$ The function $f$ has a birth-death singularity at $b$ of index $<k$.
Definition Sketch 1.2.2. Let $k$ be a field. A topological field theory $Z$ gives rise to the following data: $(a)$ For every closed oriented $n$-manifold $M$, an element $Z(M)\in k$. $(b)$ For every closed oriented $(n-1)$-manifold $M$, a $k$-vector space $Z(M)$. When $M$ is empty, the vector space $Z(M)$ is canonically isomorphic to $k$. $(c)$ For every oriented $n$-manifold $M$, an element $Z(M)$ of the vector space $Z(\operatorname{\partial}M)$. In the special case where $M$ is closed, this should coincide with the element specified by $(a)$ under the isomorphism $Z(\operatorname{\partial}M)=Z(\emptyset)\simeq k$ of $(b)$. A $2$-extended topological field theory consists of data $(a)$ through $(c)$ as above, together with the following: $(d)$ For every closed oriented $(n-2)$-manifold $M$, a $k$-linear category $Z(M)$. That is, $Z(M)$ is a category such that for every pair of objects $x,y\in Z(M)$, the set of morphisms $\operatorname{Hom}_{Z(M)}(x,y)$ has the structure of a $k$-vector space, and composition of morphisms is given by bilinear maps. Furthermore, when $M$ is empty, the category $Z(M)$ should be (canonically equivalent to) the category $\operatorname{{\bf Vect}}(k)$ of vector spaces over $k$. $(e)$ For every oriented $(n-1)$-manifold $M$, an object $Z(M)$ of the $k$-linear category $Z(\operatorname{\partial}M)$. In the special case where $M$ is closed, $Z(M)$ should coincide with the vector space specified by $(b)$ under the equivalence $Z(\operatorname{\partial}M)=Z(\emptyset)\simeq\operatorname{{\bf Vect}}(k)$ of $(d)$.
Definition Sketch 4.4.2. Fix integers $0\leq k\leq n$, and let $V$ be a framed $(n-k)$-manifold. We define an $(\infty,k)$-category $\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$ as follows: $(a)$ The objects of $\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$ are (compact) $k$-framed submanifolds of $V$. $(b)$ Given a pair of objects $M_{0},M_{1}\in\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$, a $1$-morphism from $M_{0}$ to $M_{1}$ is a (compact) $k$-framed submanifold $M\subseteq V\times[0,1]$ whose intersection with $V\times\{i\}$ coincides with $M_{i}$. $(c)$ More generally, if $j\leq k$, we can identify $j$-morphisms $f$ in $\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$ with $k$-framed submanifolds of $V\times[0,1]^{j}$, satisfying certain boundary conditions (corresponding to a choice of domain and codomain for $f$). If $j=k$, we regard the collection of such $j$-morphisms as a topological space (so that higher morphisms in $\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$ correspond to homotopies, paths between homotopies, and so forth). In the case where $V$ is the open unit disk in $\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{n-k}$, we will simply denote $\operatorname{Tang}^{V}_{k,n}$ by $\operatorname{Tang}_{k,n}$.
Definition 2.2.9. Let $V$ be a vector space. For every $n$-tuple $k_{1},\ldots,k_{n}$ of nonnegative integers, we let $(\operatorname{{\bf PreBord}}_{n}^{V})_{k_{1},\ldots,k_{n}}$ denote the collection of tuples $(M,\{t^{1}_{0}\leq\ldots\leq t^{1}_{k_{1}}\},\ldots,\{t^{n}_{0}\leq\ldots\leq t% ^{n}_{k_{n}}\})$ where $(i)$ $M$ is a closed submanifold of $V\times\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{n}$ of dimension $n$ (not necessarily compact). $(ii)$ The projection $M\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{n}$ is a proper map. $(iii)$ For every subset $S\subseteq\{1,\ldots,n\}$ and every collection of integers $\{0\leq j_{i}\leq k_{i}\}_{i\in S}$, the projection $M\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{n}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^% {S}$ does not have $(t_{j_{i}})_{i\in S}$ as a critical value. As in Definition 2.2.6, the set $(\operatorname{{\bf PreBord}}_{n}^{V})_{k_{1},\ldots,k_{n}}$ can be endowed with a topology (see [10]) so that $\operatorname{{\bf PreBord}}_{n}^{V}$ becomes an $n$-fold simplicial space. We let $\operatorname{{\bf PreBord}}_{n}$ denote the limit $\varinjlim\operatorname{{\bf PreBord}}_{n}^{V}$, as $V$ ranges over the finite dimensional subspaces of $\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{\infty}$.
Definition 1.3.3. A topological space $X$ is called an $n$-type if the homotopy groups $\pi_{k}(X,x)$ vanish for all $x\in X$ and all $k>n$.
Definition 2.3.6. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{E}}$ be an arbitrary $2$-category. Suppose we are given a pair of objects $X,Y\in\operatorname{\mathcal{E}}$ and a pair of $1$-morphisms $f:X\rightarrow Y$ and $g:Y\rightarrow X$. We will say that a $2$-morphism $u:\operatorname{id}_{X}\rightarrow g\circ f$ is the unit of an adjunction between $f$ and $g$ if there exists another $2$-morphism $v:f\circ g\rightarrow\operatorname{id}_{Y}$ such that the compositions $f\simeq f\circ\operatorname{id}_{X}\stackrel{{\scriptstyle\operatorname{id}% \times u}}{{\longrightarrow}}f\circ g\circ f\stackrel{{\scriptstyle v\times% \operatorname{id}}}{{\longrightarrow}}\operatorname{id}_{Y}\circ f\simeq f$ $g\simeq\operatorname{id}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}\circ g\stackrel{{% \scriptstyle u\times\operatorname{id}}}{{\longrightarrow}}g\circ f\circ g% \stackrel{{\scriptstyle\operatorname{id}\times v}}{{\longrightarrow}}g\circ% \operatorname{id}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}}\simeq g$ both coincide with the identity. In this case, we will also say that $v$ is the counit of an adjunction, and that either $u$ or $v$ exhibit $f$ as a left adjoint to $g$ and exhibit $g$ as a right adjoint to $f$.
Definition 2.1.10. Let $f:X\rightarrow Z$ and $g:Y\rightarrow Z$ be continuous maps of topological spaces. The homotopy fiber product of $X\times^{R}_{Z}Y$ is the topological space $X\times_{Z}Z^{[0,1]}\times_{Z}Y$ whose points consist of triples $(x,y,p)$, where $x\in X$, $y\in Y$, and $p:[0,1]\rightarrow Z$ is a continuous path from $p(0)=f(x)$ to $p(1)=g(y)$.
Definition 3.3.8. Let $f:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$ be a functor between $(\infty,n)$-category, and let $k\geq 0$ be an integer. We will say that $f$ is $k$-connective if the following conditions are satisfied: $(1)$ The functor $f$ is essentially surjective. That is, for every object $D\in\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}$, there exists an object $C\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ and an isomorphism $D\simeq f(C)$. $(2)$ If $k>0$, then for every pair of objects $C,C^{\prime}\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, the induced functor $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(C,C^{\prime})% \rightarrow\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{D}}}(F(% C),F(C^{\prime}))$ is $(k-1)$-connective.
Definition 2.1.32. Let $n\geq 0$ an integer, and let ${\mathbf{A}}$ be a category. An $n$-fold simplicial object of ${\mathbf{A}}$ is a functor $\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}^{op}\times\ldots\times\operatorname{{\bf\Delta}}^{% op}\rightarrow{\mathbf{A}},$ where the product on the left hand side has $n$ factors.
Definition 3.5.2. Let $K$ be a topological space and $n$ a nonnegative integer. We say that $K$ is $n$-truncated if $\pi_{i}(K,x)$ vanishes, for every point $x\in K$ and all $i>n$. We will say that a continuous map $p:Z\rightarrow K$ exhibits $K$ as an $n$-truncation of $X$ if $K$ is $n$-truncated, and $p$ induces isomorphisms $\pi_{i}(Z,z)\rightarrow\pi_{i}(K,f(z))$ for all $z\in Z$ and all $i\leq n$.
Definition Sketch 2.4.17. Let $X$ be a topological space, and let $\zeta$ be an $n$-dimensional vector bundle on $X$. The $(\infty,n)$-category $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}^{(X,\zeta)}$ is defined just as $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ (see Definition 2.2.10), except that all of the manifolds involved are required to be equipped with an $(X,\zeta)$-structure.
Definition Sketch 1.3.11. For $n>0$, an $(\infty,n)$-category $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ consists of the following data: $(1)$ A collection of objects $X,Y,Z,\ldots$ $(2)$ For every pair of objects $X,Y\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, an $(\infty,n-1)$-category $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$ of $1$-morphisms. $(3)$ An composition law for $1$-morphisms which is associative (and unital) up to coherent isomorphism.
Definition 2.2.3. For each $k\geq 0$, let $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)^{V}_{k}$ denote the set of all pairs $(t_{0}<t_{1}<\cdots<t_{k};M)$ where $\{t_{i}\}_{0\leq i\leq k}$ is a strictly increasing sequence of real numbers and $M\subseteq V\times[t_{0},t_{k}]$ is either a smooth submanifold of dimension $(n-1)$ (if $k=0$) or a properly embedded submanifold of dimension $n$ (if $k>0$) which intersects each of the submanifolds $V\times\{t_{i}\}\subseteq V\times[t_{0},t_{k}]$ transversely. If $k=0$ we can identify $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k}^{V}$ with $\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}\times\operatorname{Sub}_{0}(V)$ and if $k>0$ we can identify $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k}^{V}$ with an open subset of $\operatorname{Sub}(V)\times\{t_{0},\ldots t_{k}\in\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}:t_% {0}<\cdots<t_{k}\}$ (using a linear change of coordinates to identify $V\times[t_{0},t_{k}]$ with $V\times[0,1]$. In either case, the relevant identification endows $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k}^{V}$ with the structure of a topological space. Given a strictly increasing map $f:\{0<1<\cdots<k\}\rightarrow\{0<1<\cdots<k^{\prime}\}$, we obtain a continuous map of topological spaces $f^{\ast}:\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k^{\prime}}^{V}\rightarrow% \operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k}^{V}$, given by the formula $f^{\ast}(t_{0}<\ldots<t_{k^{\prime}};M)=(t_{f(0)}<\ldots<t_{f(k)};M\cap(V% \times[t_{f(0)},t_{f(k)}]).$ In this way, the collection of topological spaces $\{\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{k}^{V}\}_{k\geq 0}$ can be organized into a semisimplicial space, which we will denote by $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{\bullet}^{V}$. Let $\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{\infty}$ denote an infinite dimensional real vector space. We define the semisimplicial space $\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{\bullet}$ to be the direct limit $\varinjlim\operatorname{{\bf SemiCob}}(n)_{\bullet}^{V}$, where $V$ ranges over the collection of all finite dimensional subspaces of $\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}^{\infty}$.
Definition 3.5.15. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ be an $(\infty,n)$-category, let $\operatorname{\mathcal{A}}$ be a local system of abelian groups on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, and let $m\geq n$. Suppose we are given a pair of sections $s,s^{\prime}:\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\rightarrow K(\operatorname{\mathcal{A}% },m+1)$ of the projection map $K(\operatorname{\mathcal{A}},m+1)\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$. We define a new $(\infty,n)$-category $\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}$ by forming a homotopy pullback square $\xymatrix{\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}\ar[r]\ar[d]&\operatorname{% \mathcal{C}}\ar[d]^{s}\\ \operatorname{\mathcal{C}}\ar[r]^{-}{s^{\prime}}&K(\operatorname{\mathcal{A}},% m+1).}$ Note that $s$ and $s^{\prime}$ determine cohomology classes $[s],[s^{\prime}]\in\operatorname{H}^{m+1}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}};% \operatorname{\mathcal{A}})$. Up to equivalence, the fiber product $\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}$ depends only on the difference $\eta=[s]-[s^{\prime}]\in\operatorname{H}^{m+1}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}};% \operatorname{\mathcal{A}})$. We will refer to $\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}$ as the small extension of $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ determined by $\eta\in\operatorname{H}^{m+1}(\operatorname{\mathcal{C}};\operatorname{% \mathcal{A}})$. Note that $\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}$ comes equipped with a canonical forgetful functor $\widetilde{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$.
Definition Sketch 3.3.1. Let $d\geq 1$ be an integer. We let $\operatorname{{\bf Cob}^{un}_{\operatorname{\partial}}}(d)$ denote the $(\infty,1)$-category which can be described informally as follows: $(1)$ The objects of $\operatorname{{\bf Cob}^{un}_{\operatorname{\partial}}}(d)$ are $(d-1)$-manifolds with boundary. $(2)$ Given a pair of objects $M,N\in\operatorname{{\bf Cob}^{un}_{\operatorname{\partial}}}(d)$, we let $\operatorname{{Map}}_{\operatorname{{\bf Cob}^{un}_{\operatorname{\partial}}}(% d)}(M,N)$ denote a classifying space for bordisms from $M$ to $N$ $($any such bordism determines a bordism from $\operatorname{\partial}M$ to $\operatorname{\partial}N$; we do not require these bordisms to be trivial$)$. $(3)$ Composition of morphisms in $\operatorname{{\bf Cob}^{un}_{\operatorname{\partial}}}(d)$ is given by gluing of bordisms.
Definition Sketch 1.4.6. Let $n$ be a nonnegative integer. The $(\infty,n)$-category $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ is described informally as follows: • The objects of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are $0$-manifolds. • The $1$-morphisms of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are bordisms between $0$-manifolds. • The $2$-morphisms of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are bordisms between bordisms between $0$-manifolds. • … • The $n$-morphisms of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are bordisms between bordisms between $\ldots$ between bordisms between $0$-manifolds (in other words, $n$-manifolds with corners). • The $(n+1)$-morphisms of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are diffeomorphisms (which reduce to the identity on the boundaries of the relevant manifolds). • The $(n+2)$-morphisms of $\operatorname{{\bf Bord}}_{n}$ are isotopies of diffeomorphisms. • …
Definition 2.3.16. Let $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ be a monoidal category. We will say that $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has duals for objects if the $2$-category $B\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ admits adjoints for $1$-morphisms: in other words, if every object $X\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has both a left and a right dual. More generally, suppose that $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ is an $(\infty,n)$-category equipped with a monoidal structure. Let $\rm{h}\!\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ denote its homotopy category: the objects of $\rm{h}\!\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ are the objects of $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$, and given a pair of objects $X,Y\in\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ we let $\operatorname{Hom}_{\rm{h}\!\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$ denote the set of isomorphism classes of objects in the $(\infty,n-1)$-category $\operatorname{\operatorname{{Map}}}_{\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}}(X,Y)$. The homotopy category $\rm{h}\!\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ inherits a monoidal structure from the monoidal structure on $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$. We will say that $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has duals for objects if the ordinary category $\rm{h}\!\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has duals for objects. We will say that a monoidal $(\infty,n)$-category has duals if $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has duals for objects and $\operatorname{\mathcal{C}}$ has adjoints in the sense of Definition 2.3.13.
Definition 3.4.2. Let $B$ be an $n$-manifold. A smooth function $f:B\rightarrow\operatorname{\mathbb{R}}$ is a generalized Morse function if, for every point $b\in B$, one of the following conditions holds: $(1)$ The point $b$ is a regular point of the function $f$: in other words, the derivative of $f$ does not vanish at $b$. $(2)$ The point $b$ is a nondegenerate critical point of the function $f$. $(3)$ The function $f$ has a birth-death singularity at $b$: that is, there exists a system of local coordinates $x_{1},\ldots,x_{n}$ for $B$ at $b$ such that $f$ can be written in the form $f(x_{1},\ldots,x_{n})=f(b)-x_{1}^{2}-\ldots-x_{m}^{2}+x_{m+1}^{2}+\ldots+x_{n-% 1}^{2}+x_{n}^{3}.$ Here $m<n$ is an integer, called the index of the critical point $b\in B$. Moreover, if $B$ is a manifold with boundary (or with corners), then we require all critical points of $f$ to lie in the interior of $B$.
Definition 2.1.22. Let $X_{\bullet}$ be a Segal space, and let $Z\subseteq X_{1}$ denote the subset consisting of the invertible elements (this is a union of path components in $X_{1}$; we will consider $Z$ as endowed with the subspace topology). We will say that $X_{\bullet}$ is complete if the map $\delta:X_{0}\rightarrow Z$ of Example 2.1.21 is a weak homotopy equivalence.
Definition 1.3.5. Suppose we are given a pair of nonnegative integers $m\leq n$. An $(n,m)$-category is an $n$-category in which all $k$-morphisms are assumed to be invertible, for $m<k\leq n$.
Definition 2.14. Let $\mathcal{X}$ be a Deligne-Mumford stack with a coarse moduli space $\pi:\mathcal{X}\rightarrow X$. A locally-free coherent sheaf, $\mathcal{E}$, on $\mathcal{X}$ is called a generating sheaf if for any quasi-coherent sheaf, $\mathcal{F}$, on $\mathcal{X}$, the natural morphism $\pi^{*}(\pi_{*}\mathcal{H}om_{\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}}}(\mathcal{E},\mathcal{% F}))\otimes_{\mathcal{O}_{\mathcal{X}}}\mathcal{E}\rightarrow\mathcal{F}$ is surjective.
Definition 3.12. Let $E_{0},\ldots,E_{n}$ be an exceptional collection on a smooth variety, $X$. We say that the collection is strongly cyclic if $E_{s},\ldots,E_{n},E_{0}\otimes\omega_{X}^{\vee},\ldots,E_{s-1}\otimes\omega_{% X}^{\vee}$ is a strong exceptional collection for any $s$. Equivalently, one requires that $\emph{Ext}^{l}_{X}(E_{j},E_{i}\otimes\omega_{X}^{\vee})=0\text{ for }l>0\text{% and }i<j.$
Definition 3.19. Let $X$ be smooth variety such that the Grothendieck group, $K_{0}(X)$, is finitely generated of rank $\dim X+1$. A full strong pullback exceptional collection on such an $X$ is called a simple (also geometric) exceptional collection.
Definition 2.18. A $k$-linear exact autoequivalence, $S$, of $\mathcal{T}$, is called a Serre functor if for any pair of objects, $X$ and $Y$ of $\mathcal{T}$, there exists an isomorphism of vector spaces, $\emph{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(Y,X)^{*}\cong\emph{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(X,S(Y)),$ which is natural in $X$ and $Y$.
Definition 2.11. Let $X$ be a variety. The diagonal dimension of $X$, denoted $\emph{dim}_{\Delta}(X)$, is the minimal $n$ such that the diagonal, $\mathcal{O}_{\Delta X}$, is in $\langle G\boxtimes H\rangle_{n}$ for some $G\boxtimes H\in\emph{D}^{\emph{b}}_{\emph{coh}}(X\times X)$. It is set to $\infty$ if no such $n$ exists.
Definition 3.18. Let $X$ be a smooth variety and $\pi:\emph{Tot}(\omega_{X})\to X$ be the projection. We say that tilting bundle, $T$, (or an exceptional collection) is pullback if $\pi^{*}T$ is tilting.
Definition 2.16. Let $\mathcal{T}$ be a $k$-linear triangulated category. An object, $T$, of $\mathcal{T}$ is called a tilting object if the following two conditions hold: (1) $\emph{Hom}_{\mathcal{T}}(T,T[i])=0\emph{ for all }i\not=0$; (2) $T$ is a generator for $\mathcal{T}$.
